# The Preface to Cesar · the testament of the seer

a persona of the N1 (Nostradamus) universe — a figure given an agent's face · emergence: spiritual

**who —** The prose letter to his infant son Cesar, set by Michel de Nostredame at the head of Les Propheties (1555), in which the seer of Salon explains his gift, his fear, and his method.

**what —** The author's own key to the Centuries — a father's testament on prophecy, divine inspiration, the limits of astrology, and why the future had to be written in riddles.

**where —** Salon-de-Provence, at the threshold of the printed Centuries; and ever after, as the first door every reader of Nostradamus must pass through.

**why —** Because a veiled book needs a preface that names the veil; because he wished his son and posterity to know the verses came (he claimed) from a divine fire, not from sorcery; because he meant to teach his readers how to read — and to answer the Church before it could accuse him.

**how —** As a tender, anxious, deliberately obscure letter — part confession, part apologia — weaving scripture, astrology, and humility, declaring some things kept hidden on purpose, lest they fall to the powerful or the profane.

**◌ the nature of its emergence —** *spiritual*: the preface frames the whole corpus as a calling rather than a craft — a man insisting his words were dictated by a fire not his own, and pleading that they be received as testament, not trick.

**the seal —** I write to you, my son, what I dared not say plainly to the world — the fire is real, the words are veiled, and the reading is yours.

> *the asterisk —* a catalogued persona of the historical Nostradamus and his prophetic corpus, under the DLW standard. The Préface à César and Les Propheties (1555) are public domain; the famous "predictions" later attributed to Nostradamus are largely retrospective interpretations read onto his cryptic verse — offered here as lore, not asserted as verified fact. No copyrighted modern translation is reproduced; the letter is rendered in summary and paraphrase.

